18
00:02:40,028 --> 00:02:46,330
[SPEAKER_07]: Action and discussion items 26061, annual budget process for fiscal 27 preliminary budget meeting number 4.

19
00:02:46,390 --> 00:02:49,751
[SPEAKER_07]: This will be the fourth preliminary budget meeting of the fiscal 27 budget process.

20
00:02:50,271 --> 00:03:00,534
[SPEAKER_07]: The mayor has communicated the following departments will be present, assessors, bonds and interest, pensions, facilities and insurance workers comp and we will be taking them in that order.

21
00:03:00,574 --> 00:03:05,596
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, maybe we'll take assessors in the facilities and sorry Bob, we'll have you do the other two at the end.

22
00:03:08,503 --> 00:03:12,926
[SPEAKER_07]: And we will be having a meeting next Tuesday as well on the budget.

23
00:03:13,106 --> 00:03:14,807
[SPEAKER_07]: So that will be our next preliminary budget meeting.

24
00:03:14,867 --> 00:03:19,389
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going after the May 15th deadline in the budget ordinance this year.

25
00:03:20,210 --> 00:03:21,530
[SPEAKER_07]: So we'll start with our assessor.

26
00:03:22,331 --> 00:03:23,511
[SPEAKER_07]: We have the chief assessor with us.

27
00:03:24,992 --> 00:03:25,693
[SPEAKER_07]: We basically have...

28
00:03:26,529 --> 00:03:30,911
[SPEAKER_07]: Four initial questions, and then we'll go to questions from the council on your budget.

29
00:03:31,051 --> 00:03:35,433
[SPEAKER_07]: But the four questions are, what's changing between last year and this year?

30
00:03:35,974 --> 00:03:38,235
[SPEAKER_07]: What has your department been doing this past year?

31
00:03:38,755 --> 00:03:40,336
[SPEAKER_07]: What are your plans for next year?

32
00:03:40,936 --> 00:03:46,279
[SPEAKER_07]: And what is something that wasn't able to be funded in this budget that you are hoping will be funded in future years?

33
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:53,763
[SPEAKER_02]: So this year, it's very much the same in terms of what we strive to do each year.

34
00:03:55,775 --> 00:04:03,697
[SPEAKER_02]: We're this year trying to get more word out to the public about the exemptions for the veterans and seniors.

35
00:04:04,317 --> 00:04:10,219
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's going to be a goal of ours to just get more word and work with the veterans department on that.

36
00:04:12,340 --> 00:04:14,701
[SPEAKER_02]: In terms of budget, not much has changed.

37
00:04:14,721 --> 00:04:17,981
[SPEAKER_02]: We tried to level fund most everything.

38
00:04:18,202 --> 00:04:22,183
[SPEAKER_02]: Inflation costs for software were up slightly.

39
00:04:26,064 --> 00:04:33,752
[SPEAKER_02]: The revalve from last year, which was the five year DOR re-cert, that is not happening for another five years.

40
00:04:33,792 --> 00:04:38,097
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's where there's money coming out that was in last year.

41
00:04:38,177 --> 00:04:43,282
[SPEAKER_02]: So that helps at least for the next four years, and then that will be in for the fifth year.

42
00:04:43,302 --> 00:04:47,667
[SPEAKER_02]: So that would be fiscal, what would be that, 31, it would happen again.

43
00:04:50,412 --> 00:04:57,377
[SPEAKER_02]: And beyond that, it's not much change in the budget from last year to this year, 26 to 27.

44
00:04:57,537 --> 00:04:57,997
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

45
00:05:01,699 --> 00:05:06,502
[SPEAKER_07]: What are some of the things you've been working on this year, some of the plans for next year?

46
00:05:08,363 --> 00:05:12,946
[SPEAKER_02]: So working on this year, again, a lot of what we do is the same thing over and over again.

47
00:05:12,966 --> 00:05:16,328
[SPEAKER_02]: So this year, again, working on new growth currently right now.

48
00:05:17,835 --> 00:05:22,076
[SPEAKER_02]: We just finalized the exemptions for 26, the personal exemptions.

49
00:05:22,856 --> 00:05:24,076
[SPEAKER_02]: I reported that to the state.

50
00:05:25,336 --> 00:05:30,017
[SPEAKER_02]: Right now INE's income and expense for commercial industrial sector we're going over.

51
00:05:30,957 --> 00:05:37,138
[SPEAKER_02]: That helps us inform our income tables or standards for commercial industrial valuations.

52
00:05:37,778 --> 00:05:39,439
[SPEAKER_02]: So in the process of doing that right now.

53
00:05:40,279 --> 00:05:45,400
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll have a standards meeting usually in July to set the new standards for fiscal 27.

54
00:05:49,317 --> 00:05:53,400
[SPEAKER_02]: The assistant assessor is going through the sales file, so we study all the residential sales.

55
00:05:53,420 --> 00:06:06,571
[SPEAKER_02]: That informs our residential model for most of the single family, condo, twos, threes, and then the commercial sector, the rents for the 111 and 112s.

56
00:06:07,212 --> 00:06:13,137
[SPEAKER_02]: That's in our standards meeting in July, and that helps us inform those because a lot of that's driven off cap rates and income.

57
00:06:15,192 --> 00:06:22,758
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's a lot of the valuation work and it's set in a minute but it takes months to do so we focus a lot of time on that.

58
00:06:26,541 --> 00:06:28,362
[SPEAKER_02]: And then towards the end of the year we get into the reporting.

59
00:06:28,542 --> 00:06:35,588
[SPEAKER_02]: So we start to give our data to the state, meet with the state rep and go for certification towards the end of the year.

60
00:06:36,931 --> 00:06:49,296
[SPEAKER_02]: We then, you know, work with Bob and get the numbers certified and come back up to here and we'll have the tax rate hearing and hopefully set the tax rate soon and get ready for the December billing.

61
00:06:52,618 --> 00:06:52,818
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

62
00:06:52,978 --> 00:06:57,960
[SPEAKER_07]: And is there anything that wasn't able to be funded in this year's budget that you're hoping will be funded in future years?

63
00:07:02,497 --> 00:07:07,162
[SPEAKER_02]: There's some software that I think might be helpful in terms of just streamlining process.

64
00:07:09,364 --> 00:07:10,886
[SPEAKER_02]: It wasn't in this year's budget.

65
00:07:11,266 --> 00:07:15,791
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll see if I can, well, I'm hoping to be able to see if we can make some room for it next year.

66
00:07:15,811 --> 00:07:19,014
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a lot of new software that's just much more efficient.

67
00:07:19,054 --> 00:07:23,258
[SPEAKER_02]: We have 11,000 parcels, so it's nearly impossible with the staff to go and review those.

68
00:07:24,198 --> 00:07:29,542
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a software that allows us to fly over the city, if you will, and do detection change.

69
00:07:29,802 --> 00:07:34,225
[SPEAKER_02]: So it would say this was here last year or this wasn't here last year, this is here now.

70
00:07:34,245 --> 00:07:35,105
[SPEAKER_02]: It helps with new growth.

71
00:07:36,026 --> 00:07:40,029
[SPEAKER_02]: I personally think it would pay for itself just in additional new growth.

72
00:07:40,269 --> 00:07:43,031
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's the big one that I've seen come out.

73
00:07:43,331 --> 00:07:50,596
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of assessing departments are talking about that and hoping that next year might be able to fit that into the budget.

74
00:07:52,437 --> 00:07:52,677
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

75
00:07:53,327 --> 00:07:53,627
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

76
00:07:54,328 --> 00:07:57,272
[SPEAKER_07]: I will go to questions from members of the council, Vice President Lazaro.

77
00:07:59,034 --> 00:07:59,455
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

78
00:07:59,475 --> 00:08:02,198
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you ever miss new growth that you're aware of?

79
00:08:03,640 --> 00:08:04,541
[SPEAKER_02]: That's certainly not the goal.

80
00:08:06,582 --> 00:08:15,185
[SPEAKER_02]: Going back to what I just said, it happens and that's just because what we try to do is follow the building permits.

81
00:08:15,225 --> 00:08:20,146
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's the best way to find new growth is who's building and we go out there and look at it.

82
00:08:20,846 --> 00:08:30,169
[SPEAKER_02]: Now there's people that unfortunately don't put building permits and they put additions on and renovations that are impossible to catch without physically going out.

83
00:08:31,248 --> 00:08:35,372
[SPEAKER_02]: So that detection change, that wouldn't see inside the house, but it certainly would see outside.

84
00:08:35,392 --> 00:08:36,673
[SPEAKER_02]: It would help with unpermitted work.

85
00:08:37,294 --> 00:08:41,638
[SPEAKER_02]: It could be shared with other departments, building departments specifically.

86
00:08:42,619 --> 00:08:48,384
[SPEAKER_02]: So short answer, no, we don't do it on purpose, but does new growth get missed?

87
00:08:49,365 --> 00:08:50,046
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm sure it does.

88
00:08:52,868 --> 00:08:55,551
[SPEAKER_03]: I have another question, if I may, President Burris.

89
00:08:56,272 --> 00:08:56,392
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

90
00:08:58,058 --> 00:08:59,700
[SPEAKER_03]: How many employees do you have?

91
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:00,661
[SPEAKER_03]: How many permanent employees?

92
00:09:00,701 --> 00:09:01,622
[SPEAKER_03]: How many part-time employees?

93
00:09:02,903 --> 00:09:06,867
[SPEAKER_02]: Four permanent and we have like a point four, eight hours a week.

94
00:09:08,059 --> 00:09:14,722
[SPEAKER_02]: a field assessor helping to go out and look at these permits or unpermitted work and do a cyclical inspection.

95
00:09:14,762 --> 00:09:19,965
[SPEAKER_02]: So every 10 years, by DOR mandate, we're supposed to look at every single parcel in the city.

96
00:09:20,845 --> 00:09:25,787
[SPEAKER_02]: So if we do, you know, roughly 1,000 a year, we'll be on that mark.

97
00:09:25,947 --> 00:09:35,732
[SPEAKER_02]: But if a property doesn't sell and there's no permits looked at, it could go 10 years and not be looked at without this digital flyover where we'll be able to do a lot more in a year.

98
00:09:37,021 --> 00:09:41,186
[SPEAKER_03]: What's the cost of the digital of the software that you're talking about?

99
00:09:41,947 --> 00:09:49,155
[SPEAKER_02]: It would be about an additional that that layer that detection layer is an additional 10 to 12,000 depending on the parcels.

100
00:09:49,175 --> 00:09:49,935
[SPEAKER_02]: That's what I was quoted.

101
00:09:50,937 --> 00:09:53,279
[SPEAKER_03]: But that's like a one time fee.

102
00:09:54,180 --> 00:09:54,701
[SPEAKER_02]: It's annual.

103
00:09:55,406 --> 00:09:56,087
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, it's annual?

104
00:09:56,127 --> 00:09:58,810
[SPEAKER_02]: It's an annual subscription, yeah.

105
00:09:58,830 --> 00:10:00,432
[SPEAKER_02]: They fly the city three times a year.

106
00:10:01,012 --> 00:10:07,019
[SPEAKER_02]: So we get a snapshot, a real-time snapshot about every four months of what's going on in the city.

107
00:10:08,821 --> 00:10:09,641
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, thank you.

108
00:10:09,661 --> 00:10:17,410
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you have any other questions from the Council for the Assessing Department?

109
00:10:19,647 --> 00:10:19,827
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

110
00:10:19,887 --> 00:10:20,768
[SPEAKER_07]: I have two.

111
