151
00:12:02,212 --> 00:12:02,572
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course.

152
00:12:02,813 --> 00:12:04,093
[SPEAKER_06]: My name's David McIntyre.

153
00:12:04,193 --> 00:12:05,914
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm the director of facilities.

154
00:12:06,454 --> 00:12:07,635
[SPEAKER_06]: I started back in January.

155
00:12:08,382 --> 00:12:24,270
[SPEAKER_06]: I come from, you know, over 10 years of facilities experience, and I'm a Medford resident who is looking at getting more involved in my city and found this opportunity and threw my name in the hat to try to join this group we have at City Hall.

156
00:12:25,130 --> 00:12:25,390
[SPEAKER_06]: Great.

157
00:12:27,731 --> 00:12:28,031
[SPEAKER_07]: Awesome.

158
00:12:28,071 --> 00:12:32,594
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, thank you for being here, and we'll go through that same kind of list of questions.

159
00:12:33,540 --> 00:12:39,164
[SPEAKER_07]: What's the difference between last year's budget, the current fiscal year and the upcoming fiscal year, 26 and 27?

160
00:12:39,224 --> 00:12:43,226
[SPEAKER_07]: What has your department been working on this year?

161
00:12:43,707 --> 00:12:45,248
[SPEAKER_07]: What are your plans for next year?

162
00:12:45,548 --> 00:12:50,511
[SPEAKER_07]: And what was something that wasn't able to be funded in the upcoming budget that you'd like to see funded in the future?

163
00:12:51,191 --> 00:12:51,372
[SPEAKER_06]: Great.

164
00:12:52,072 --> 00:12:58,696
[SPEAKER_06]: So I've worked since January to best understand the financial situation of my department.

165
00:12:59,966 --> 00:13:04,509
[SPEAKER_06]: Basically, the difference between last year and this year, there is a decent amount of increases.

166
00:13:05,489 --> 00:13:07,090
[SPEAKER_06]: Utilities continue to go up.

167
00:13:07,411 --> 00:13:10,493
[SPEAKER_06]: Those rates, I don't believe, are formally set until December.

168
00:13:11,093 --> 00:13:16,696
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is based off of an 8% increase between heating fuel and utilities for those increases.

169
00:13:17,717 --> 00:13:21,259
[SPEAKER_06]: Repairs and maintenance material costs, again, continue to rise.

170
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:23,941
[SPEAKER_06]: So we show an increase there as well.

171
00:13:25,442 --> 00:13:26,342
[SPEAKER_06]: In regards to

172
00:13:28,991 --> 00:13:39,213
[SPEAKER_06]: What we've been doing since I've arrived has been a lot of kind of triage work to best understand what's going on with the different buildings, quite a few buildings that I'm responsible for.

173
00:13:41,403 --> 00:13:55,948
[SPEAKER_06]: I have been putting that all together, responding to those individual occurrences and getting the best idea of how to transition over to preventative maintenance, which will be one of my goals going forward into the next year and into the next however many years.

174
00:13:56,408 --> 00:14:01,570
[SPEAKER_06]: The more things we can transition to preventative maintenance, the more we can control facilities costs.

175
00:14:02,570 --> 00:14:10,332
[SPEAKER_06]: by getting things set on schedules to be taken care of and not waiting until equipment and what sort kind of falls apart.

176
00:14:10,972 --> 00:14:11,592
[SPEAKER_07]: So in.

177
00:14:13,193 --> 00:14:15,433
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, sorry, I just shut off your microphone by accident.

178
00:14:15,913 --> 00:14:16,474
[SPEAKER_07]: It's back on.

179
00:14:17,014 --> 00:14:20,475
[SPEAKER_07]: What I was going to say is if there's any way you can make the air quieter in this room.

180
00:14:21,575 --> 00:14:22,475
[SPEAKER_07]: But keep going, sorry.

181
00:14:22,715 --> 00:14:24,376
[SPEAKER_06]: I can look into that tomorrow morning for you.

182
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:32,845
[SPEAKER_06]: But yes, so essentially my main goal would be to transition as many things possible to a preventative maintenance schedule.

183
00:14:33,306 --> 00:14:35,527
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, HVAC systems are a great example of that.

184
00:14:35,607 --> 00:14:43,014
[SPEAKER_06]: If they get tended to on an annual or even semi-monthly basis, then we will catch things instead of waiting until stuff happens.

185
00:14:45,876 --> 00:14:47,297
[SPEAKER_06]: What are the other prompts?

186
00:14:47,758 --> 00:14:49,239
