00:46:20,989 --> 00:46:21,929
[SPEAKER_07]: First is on the JIC.

561
00:46:21,969 --> 00:46:32,057
[SPEAKER_07]: Do you know why or do you have any insight into why we see less, why we're seeing a lower increase than other communities and higher than others?

562
00:46:32,137 --> 00:46:34,579
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that a formula question or a number of beneficiaries?

563
00:46:34,639 --> 00:46:35,339
[SPEAKER_05]: I really don't know.

564
00:46:35,359 --> 00:46:36,040
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

565
00:46:37,348 --> 00:46:44,131
[SPEAKER_07]: Does the GIC provide any sort of explanation to the city about the rate change every year, or they just send us a number?

566
00:46:45,471 --> 00:46:47,292
[SPEAKER_05]: They just send us a number, basically.

567
00:46:47,332 --> 00:46:58,136
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, they don't even... Remember, the GIC consists of eight, nine different plans depending on what it is.

568
00:46:59,797 --> 00:47:03,978
[SPEAKER_05]: And some of those plans went up by more than 9%.

569
00:47:04,438 --> 00:47:06,019
[SPEAKER_05]: Some of them went up by less than 9%.

570
00:47:06,955 --> 00:47:10,338
[SPEAKER_05]: And I would think that that drives a lot of how that works.

571
00:47:10,438 --> 00:47:17,403
[SPEAKER_05]: It's whatever agreements cities and towns have with their employees and who takes which plan.

572
00:47:18,905 --> 00:47:21,306
[SPEAKER_05]: So there's two different Harvard Pilgrim plans.

573
00:47:21,366 --> 00:47:22,247
[SPEAKER_05]: There's Unicare.

574
00:47:22,307 --> 00:47:23,588
[SPEAKER_05]: There's the retiree plans.

575
00:47:24,189 --> 00:47:28,992
[SPEAKER_05]: So if you want the gory details when I'm trying to calculate what

576
00:47:32,053 --> 00:47:35,915
[SPEAKER_05]: the cost is going to be, I know what the increases are for each plan.

577
00:47:36,495 --> 00:47:38,696
[SPEAKER_05]: I know who's on each plan right now.

578
00:47:39,756 --> 00:47:48,540
[SPEAKER_05]: So I calculate that budget for the next year and then I add, you know, 10% for new employees, people switching plans, et cetera.

579
00:47:49,321 --> 00:47:51,502
[SPEAKER_05]: Roughly, that's roughly how it's calculated.

580
00:47:52,842 --> 00:47:55,163
[SPEAKER_05]: It's another big, big spreadsheet.

581
00:47:56,304 --> 00:47:59,185
[SPEAKER_05]: So try to get it as close as I can.

582
00:48:00,762 --> 00:48:03,843
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, we'll go to HR Director Crowley.

583
00:48:07,385 --> 00:48:08,426
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, President Bezos.

584
00:48:08,506 --> 00:48:14,148
[SPEAKER_00]: I think you may have asked why our increase is less than other communities in the Commonwealth.

585
00:48:14,208 --> 00:48:16,269
[SPEAKER_00]: Was that a question you asked or did I hear that wrong?

586
00:48:16,709 --> 00:48:22,452
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, yeah, just trying to understand if we're in the middle of the pack, is there a reason that we're in the middle of the pack?

587
00:48:23,492 --> 00:48:28,895
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, so because GIC has such a large volume of participants,

588
00:48:29,618 --> 00:48:36,741
[SPEAKER_00]: they're able to give a better rate than say like a blue car, blue cross blue shield or a private habit pilgrim.

589
00:48:36,761 --> 00:48:43,504
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's why you see we're kind of in the middle because those private insurances don't have such a large pool like the GIC.

590
00:48:43,524 --> 00:48:52,468
[SPEAKER_00]: So they're able to, to give us a better rate through the GIC than if we went out outsourced through like a direct blue cross blue shield type of situation.

591
00:48:53,688 --> 00:48:53,949
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure.

592
00:48:54,229 --> 00:48:54,449
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry.

593
00:48:54,469 --> 00:48:56,570
[SPEAKER_07]: I think I met, um, within the GIC,

594
00:48:58,877 --> 00:49:03,279
[SPEAKER_07]: Were you saying, Bob, that there's other cities that are going up 20% because they're not in the GIC?

595
00:49:04,599 --> 00:49:05,960
[SPEAKER_05]: That's just what I've heard from others.

596
00:49:06,820 --> 00:49:07,020
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

597
00:49:07,100 --> 00:49:17,444
[SPEAKER_05]: Basically, every city and town in Massachusetts and probably nationwide is experiencing large health insurance premium raises.

598
00:49:18,525 --> 00:49:20,465
[SPEAKER_05]: So this is just gossip around.

599
00:49:21,806 --> 00:49:22,106
[SPEAKER_05]: Got it.

600
00:49:22,126 --> 00:49:24,167
[SPEAKER_05]: So I don't know if they're specifically in the GIC.

601
00:49:24,227 --> 00:49:27,068
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't know what their makeup in the GIC is.

602
00:49:28,020 --> 00:49:34,143
[SPEAKER_05]: What, you know, who's getting which plan or whether or not they're on Blue Cross Blue Shield or private Harvard Pilgrim.

603
00:49:34,703 --> 00:49:40,385
[SPEAKER_05]: I just know that other cities and towns have experienced larger increases than we are experiencing this year.

604
00:49:41,046 --> 00:49:41,286
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

605
00:49:42,646 --> 00:49:43,147
[SPEAKER_07]: Two other things.

606
00:49:43,187 --> 00:49:46,688
[SPEAKER_07]: I noticed the unemployment budget's going down pretty significantly.

607
00:49:46,768 --> 00:49:49,189
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that, what's that a factor of?

608
00:49:50,450 --> 00:49:55,372
[SPEAKER_05]: That's just based on numbers that I've seen recently.

609
00:49:55,392 --> 00:49:57,193
[SPEAKER_05]: It does seem to have gone down.

610
00:49:58,933 --> 00:50:01,755
[SPEAKER_05]: We might have cut a large check for something.

611
00:50:02,955 --> 00:50:10,899
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't know why our actuals are up that much, but it's not a large part of the budget, really.

612
00:50:11,299 --> 00:50:14,360
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'd have to look at that.

613
00:50:14,380 --> 00:50:17,842
[SPEAKER_05]: I think we had in 26, we had to make up

614
00:50:23,096 --> 00:50:23,897
[SPEAKER_05]: We're working on that.

615
00:50:23,937 --> 00:50:29,501
[SPEAKER_05]: We had to make up some underpayment from many years before.

616
00:50:30,262 --> 00:50:31,403
[SPEAKER_05]: So we've made that up.

617
00:50:31,523 --> 00:50:42,152
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's, you know, that's what I came up with when I was looking at the year over year budgets for this expenditures.

618
00:50:43,833 --> 00:50:44,574
[SPEAKER_05]: I might have been wrong.

619
00:50:45,875 --> 00:50:47,036
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe I should have asked for another 25K.

620
00:50:52,541 --> 00:50:58,665
[SPEAKER_07]: And then the last thing is on our insurance premiums, police liability, and the ordinary expenses.

621
00:51:00,627 --> 00:51:02,368
[SPEAKER_07]: What are those insurance premiums?

622
00:51:02,388 --> 00:51:05,971
[SPEAKER_07]: Does that include general liability insurance for the city from lawsuits?

623
00:51:06,011 --> 00:51:07,272
[SPEAKER_05]: That's exactly what that is.

624
00:51:07,632 --> 00:51:07,912
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

625
00:51:08,212 --> 00:51:16,359
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's determined, that's what I was told by the Jay Ruddy corporate representative who does our insurance and that's for.

626
00:51:17,109 --> 00:51:21,832
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, building, cars, police, police vehicles, all of that fun stuff.

627
00:51:22,692 --> 00:51:22,973
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

628
00:51:24,193 --> 00:51:28,176
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that also covering us from personnel, lawsuits, settlement?

629
00:51:28,196 --> 00:51:36,981
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, the city's been in a pretty significant number of settlements and issues in arbitration with unions and employees.

630
00:51:37,742 --> 00:51:40,643
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that, at what point does our insurance kick in?

631
00:51:41,524 --> 00:51:43,245
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that one policy there for?

632
00:51:46,843 --> 00:51:50,145
[SPEAKER_05]: personnel issues would not be covered by this.

633
00:51:50,185 --> 00:52:01,073
[SPEAKER_05]: This is like if, you know, you walk into City Hall and trip over a wet floor.

634
00:52:01,393 --> 00:52:12,121
[SPEAKER_05]: Those, you know, other settlements or, you know, if there are labor disputes or something like that, that would not be covered by these policies, to my knowledge.

635
00:52:13,048 --> 00:52:18,452
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so these policies don't cover like MCAD complaints, or labor disputes, or arbitrations with unions.

636
00:52:18,472 --> 00:52:26,257
[SPEAKER_07]: This is just about if there's a vehicle accident, or someone falls on a sidewalk, or does this cover, for example, like a sewer backup?

637
00:52:26,357 --> 00:52:31,720
[SPEAKER_05]: This is your homeowner's insurance, and your auto liability, and all that sort of stuff.

638
00:52:32,100 --> 00:52:42,247
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so this is just covering like personal injuries, or if a vehicle or private property is damaged due to the city.

639
00:52:42,767 --> 00:52:42,947
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

640
00:52:43,668 --> 00:52:43,928
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

641
00:52:44,028 --> 00:52:47,611
[SPEAKER_07]: And is that just a monthly premium and this is the total?

642
00:52:47,631 --> 00:52:48,631
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, it's a monthly premium.

643
00:52:49,612 --> 00:52:53,175
[SPEAKER_05]: These are based on, he said it was going to go up between four and a half to five percent.

644
00:52:53,315 --> 00:52:54,756
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's what I put into the budget.

645
00:52:55,136 --> 00:52:55,397
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

646
00:52:57,038 --> 00:52:57,298
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

647
00:52:57,518 --> 00:53:03,543
[SPEAKER_07]: It would be helpful to understand, you know, are there, what is the city's liability insurance in these other matters?

648
00:53:04,523 --> 00:53:05,844
[SPEAKER_07]: And does that come out of this budget?

649
00:53:05,884 --> 00:53:07,265
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that in the law department budget?

650
00:53:08,666 --> 00:53:10,408
[SPEAKER_07]: Because we're just trying to understand where.

651
00:53:11,788 --> 00:53:15,349
[SPEAKER_07]: When the city's being sued and settling, who's paying for that?

652
00:53:15,429 --> 00:53:16,830
[SPEAKER_07]: What accounts is it coming out of?

653
00:53:17,870 --> 00:53:20,692
[SPEAKER_07]: What insurance policies are covering and addressing that?

654
00:53:21,552 --> 00:53:28,655
[SPEAKER_07]: And what's the end cost to the residents for those lawsuits and those decisions?

655
00:53:31,696 --> 00:53:36,378
[SPEAKER_07]: So I guess my question is, is there any other insurance outside of this budget?

656
00:53:38,958 --> 00:53:40,558
[SPEAKER_07]: like in the case of a lawsuit?

657
00:53:41,139 --> 00:53:41,319
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

658
00:53:42,079 --> 00:53:42,220
[SPEAKER_07]: No.

659
00:53:42,740 --> 00:53:43,060
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

660
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:44,861
[SPEAKER_05]: Not that I am aware of, no.

661
00:53:45,441 --> 00:53:45,662
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

662
00:53:45,682 --> 00:53:52,646
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, do we have any other questions for the CFO on the insurance budget?

663
